  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do bottle caps work in Pokemon Sun / Moon?",
  "response": "In **Pok\u00e9mon Sun** and **Pok\u00e9mon Moon**, **Bottle Caps** are special items used to enhance a Pok\u00e9mon's **Individual Values (IVs)** through a feature called **Hyper Training**. IVs are hidden stats that determine a Pok\u00e9mon's potential in various attributes like Attack, Defense, Speed, etc. Maximizing these IVs can significantly improve a Pok\u00e9mon's performance in battles, making them more competitive in both in-game challenges and player-versus-player (PvP) battles.\n\n### **What Are Bottle Caps?**\n\n- **Bottle Caps** are consumable items that allow players to effectively \"train\" their Pok\u00e9mon by maximizing their IVs without needing to catch or breed Pok\u00e9mon with perfect natural stats.\n- Each Bottle Cap can be used to maximize the IV of **one specific stat** (e.g., Attack, Defense, Speed) up to the maximum value of **31**.\n\n### **How Hyper Training Works**\n\n1. **Accessing Hyper Training:**\n   - To use Bottle Caps for Hyper Training, you need access to the **Battle Tree**, located on Poni Island, similar to the Battle Frontier from previous generations.\n   - After completing certain challenges or reaching specific milestones within the Battle Tree, you'll unlock the Hyper Training feature.\n\n2. **Using Bottle Caps:**\n   - Once Hyper Training is unlocked, you can select a Pok\u00e9mon whose IVs you wish to enhance.\n   - Choose the specific stat you want to maximize and apply a Bottle Cap to that stat.\n   - This action will set the chosen stat's IV to **31** for battle purposes, effectively making it perfect.\n\n3. **Limitations:**\n   - **Bottle Caps** can only be used once per stat per Pok\u00e9mon.\n   - In **Pok\u00e9mon Sun** and **Pok\u00e9mon Moon**, only standard Bottle Caps are available, which means you can enhance one stat at a time. **Gold Bottle Caps**, which allow you to maximize all six IVs simultaneously, are introduced in later generations (Pok\u00e9mon Sword and Shield) and are not available in Sun and Moon.\n   - The actual IV values of the Pok\u00e9mon do not change; Hyper Training only affects how the IVs are utilized in battles. This distinction is crucial for players who might trade Pok\u00e9mon, as the enhanced stats won't carry over.\n\n### **Obtaining Bottle Caps**\n\n- **Battle Tree Rewards:** Participate in and excel at challenges within the Battle Tree to earn Bottle Caps as rewards.\n- **In-Game Events:** Occasionally, Bottle Caps can be obtained through special in-game events or distributions.\n- **Trading:** Players can also trade with others to obtain Bottle Caps if they're in short supply.\n\n### **Strategic Use of Bottle Caps**\n\n- **Competitive Battles:** Maximizing key stats can give your Pok\u00e9mon a significant edge in battles, especially in formats where every point matters.\n- **Team Optimization:** Focus on enhancing stats that complement your team's strategy. For example, maximizing a Pok\u00e9mon's Speed can help it strike first in battles, while maximizing Attack or Special Attack can increase its damage output.\n\n### **Summary**\n\nIn **Pok\u00e9mon Sun** and **Pok\u00e9mon Moon**, **Bottle Caps** are valuable resources that enable players to enhance their Pok\u00e9mon's battle capabilities by maximizing individual stats through **Hyper Training**. This feature allows for greater customization and optimization of your Pok\u00e9mon team, making it easier to compete against tougher challenges and other trainers.\n\n---\n\n*Note: While Hyper Training and Bottle Caps significantly enhance a Pok\u00e9mon's performance in battles, they do not permanently alter the Pok\u00e9mon's actual IVs. This means that the boosts are only applicable in battle scenarios and won't affect the Pok\u00e9mon's stats in other contexts, such as trading or certain in-game evaluations.*",
